Apparitores, from apparere, were public servants, that always ‘'‘ appeared” with the magistrates, and attended to and executed their orders.

The toqa was the characteristic dress of the Romans, as the pallium was of the Greeks: it was a loose robe worn over the tunica, the coat 01· jacket which had no sleeves: during war it was exchanged for the paludamentum. Magistrates and the sons of the nobility, until the age of seventeen, wore one that had a fringe or border of purple all round, and this was called toqa praetexta, or “ the bordered gown.’'
